 If you're new to Hong Kong, I just want to say this.

22
00:00:47,000 --> 00:00:51,000
 There's amazing great churches in our city, lots of great churches in our city.

23
00:00:51,000 --> 00:00:54,000
 If you're new, we encourage you to get out there and experience

24
00:00:54,000 --> 00:00:57,000
 and to see some of the churches in our city.

25
00:00:57,000 --> 00:01:01,000
 But every single church in here in Hong Kong would say the same thing.

26
00:01:01,000 --> 00:01:06,000
 You are not in Hong Kong by mistake.

27
00:01:06,000 --> 00:01:09,000
 I'm biased because I've lived here for 40 years.

28
00:01:09,000 --> 00:01:13,000
 But God is doing something in this city I think that is unprecedented.

29
00:01:13,000 --> 00:01:17,000
 And you're a Christian, you're a believer, and you've been brought to this city.

30
00:01:17,000 --> 00:01:21,000
 And I believe the Lord is about to light a fire in you.

31
00:01:21,000 --> 00:01:24,000
 I believe that you came here for work, and work is awesome,

32
00:01:24,000 --> 00:01:26,000
 and there's lots going on in your work, and that's great.

33
00:01:26,000 --> 00:01:28,000
 But I believe that you're in this city for something far greater

34
00:01:28,000 --> 00:01:30,000
 than what you're doing Monday to Friday.

35
00:01:30,000 --> 00:01:35,000
 I believe that you're here because the Lord is actually bringing the sheep,

36
00:01:35,000 --> 00:01:38,000
 the community that he needs in his city for this time.

37
00:01:38,000 --> 00:01:42,000
 And so you bring gifts, you bring heart, you bring life,

38
00:01:42,000 --> 00:01:47,000
 you bring experience that the church of Hong Kong desperately needs in this season.

39
00:01:47,000 --> 00:01:49,000
 You are not here by mistake, amen?

40
00:01:49,000 --> 00:01:52,000
 So if you're new here, I want to do a brave thing.

41
00:01:52,000 --> 00:01:54,000
 Could you just stand if you're new to Hong Kong?

42
00:01:54,000 --> 00:01:56,000
 You just put your hand up. I'd love you just to stand.

43
00:01:56,000 --> 00:01:59,000
 Could you stand with me? Come on. Upper house, lower house.

44
00:01:59,000 --> 00:02:01,000
 Come on, stand.

45
00:02:01,000 --> 00:02:05,000
 Yes!

46
00:02:05,000 --> 00:02:08,000
 All right.

47
00:02:08,000 --> 00:02:12,000
 Everybody else, everybody else,

48
00:02:12,000 --> 00:02:14,000
 could you just stretch out your hands towards these people?

49
00:02:14,000 --> 00:02:16,000
 Can we pray for them? Let's just pray.

50
00:02:16,000 --> 00:02:20,000
 Father, we want to pray right now. Lord, we welcome these guys to Hong Kong.

51
00:02:20,000 --> 00:02:24,000
 Hong Kong is not necessarily an easy place to fit into sometimes.

52
00:02:24,000 --> 00:02:27,000
 Lord, it's crazy. There are lots of things happening.

53
00:02:27,000 --> 00:02:31,000
 Crazy work hours. It's an expensive place to live.

54
00:02:31,000 --> 00:02:33,000
 Lord, we want to pray first of all for each of these people,

55
00:02:33,000 --> 00:02:38,000
 that they would just logistically, relationally, emotionally,

56
00:02:38,000 --> 00:02:40,000
 that they would adapt to Hong Kong,

57
00:02:40,000 --> 00:02:43,000
 that you would enable them to find their feet quickly.

58
00:02:43,000 --> 00:02:46,000
 So Lord, we thank you that you've sent them.

59
00:02:46,000 --> 00:02:48,000
 And Father, you have sent them to this city.

60
00:02:48,000 --> 00:02:51,000
 These are the sent ones in this season.

61
00:02:51,000 --> 00:02:55,000
 And so Father, we recognize that they bring and they carry with them gifts,

62
00:02:55,000 --> 00:02:57,000
 an anointing and heart that Hong Kong needs,

63
00:02:57,000 --> 00:03:01,000
 that this church community needs, that our city needs.

64
00:03:01,000 --> 00:03:05,000
 And we want to pray now that you would release a fresh anointing over these ones.

65
00:03:05,000 --> 00:03:09,000
 Lord, you have brought them into this city, this fragrant harbor for this season.

66
00:03:09,000 --> 00:03:12,000
 And Lord, I want to pray that your spirit, Lord, would just enable them.

67
00:03:12,000 --> 00:03:14,000
 Where they're homesick, that you would meet them

68
00:03:14,000 --> 00:03:16,000
 and that you would speak life into them.

69
00:03:16,000 --> 00:03:18,000
 Lord, where they're beginning to get settled,

70
00:03:18,000 --> 00:03:20,000
 that you would enable them to put roots down.

71
00:03:20,000 --> 00:03:23,000
 And Lord, I want to release a new season.

72
00:03:23,000 --> 00:03:26,000
 I see oil being poured out upon you.

73
00:03:26,000 --> 00:03:30,000
 I want to pray that the oil of Jesus for this season,

74
00:03:30,000 --> 00:03:33,000
 the anointing that he has for you, would fall upon you

75
00:03:33,000 --> 00:03:37,000
 and that you would be able to work in the workplace, build relationships,

76
00:03:37,000 --> 00:03:40,000
 do the things that you do, get connected to community,

77
00:03:40,000 --> 00:03:45,000
 get connected to a church in a way that will flourish you and flourish Hong Kong.

78
00:03:45,000 --> 00:03:47,000
 We are so glad that you are here.

79
00:03:47,000 --> 00:03:49,000
 And we pray this in Jesus' name.

80
00:03:49,000 --> 00:03:51,000
 Everyone says, "Amen."

81
00:03:51,000 --> 00:03:53,000
 Welcome, everyone. Welcome.

82
00:03:53,000 --> 00:03:57,000
 By the way, by the way, we don't do that every week.

83
00:03:57,000 --> 00:03:59,000
 So that was special for you.

84
00:03:59,000 --> 00:04:02,000
 I'm excited. I'm so grateful for Pastor Ellison

85
00:04:02,000 --> 00:04:06,000
 and just this summer series that we've been in, the book of James.

86
00:04:06,000 --> 00:04:11,000
 And then for Phil and for Ellison that have taught and preached in this series so far to this point.

87
00:04:11,000 --> 00:04:14,000
 Phil brought a great message on that typhoon Sunday.

88
00:04:14,000 --> 00:04:17,000
 He felt so bad for Phil that he couldn't be here to deliver it in person.

89
00:04:17,000 --> 00:04:19,000
 But a great message on the idea of pure religion.

90
00:04:19,000 --> 00:04:21,000
 What does pure religion look like?

91
00:04:21,000 --> 00:04:22,000
 And really that's the heart.

92
00:04:22,000 --> 00:04:25,000
 That's the thesis for James throughout this whole letter is,

93
00:04:25,000 --> 00:04:30,000
 how do we understand what it is to be purified in the relationship that we have with our Father through Jesus?

94
00:04:30,000 --> 00:04:32,000
 And so that was week one.

95
00:04:32,000 --> 00:04:36,000
 Week two, Ellison brought a powerful word around faith and deeds last week.

96
00:04:36,000 --> 00:04:40,000
 And what does it mean to wrestle with the idea that we don't just profess a belief,

97
00:04:40,000 --> 00:04:43,000
 but that actually changes and impacts the way in which we live.

98
00:04:43,000 --> 00:04:49,000
 And I want to kind of build on that a little bit as we move into the third chapter of James here this morning.

99
00:04:49,000 --> 00:04:55,000
 And we look at a topic that I think is very central to James' heart for the people that he's writing to.

100
00:04:55,000 --> 00:05:00,000
 Remember, he's writing to a community of people that are facing persecution,

101
00:05:00,000 --> 00:05:04,000
 facing hostility for their faith and their environment, facing division amongst themselves,

102
00:05:04,000 --> 00:05:08,000
 trying to settle in to what it means to be community together.

103
00:05:08,000 --> 00:05:15,000
 And in the third chapter, the heart of his letter, in chapters one and two, James has been pretty direct.

104
00:05:15,000 --> 00:05:17,000
 It's almost been like he's been a little bit strong.

105
00:05:17,000 --> 00:05:20,000
 He's been like a little bit of a tell you off for all the things.

106
00:05:20,000 --> 00:05:24,000
 But by the time he gets to chapter three, this pastoral heart for James comes out.

107
00:05:24,000 --> 00:05:30,000
 And when I read James and I get into the flow of his arguments and then I come into chapter three,

108
00:05:30,000 --> 00:05:35,000
 it almost sounds like James is like kind of just hushing down a little bit.

109
00:05:35,000 --> 00:05:40,000
 Like he's wanting his community just to take a moment, to take a breath.

110
00:05:40,000 --> 00:05:43,000
 And he starts, we'll see this in a moment, but he starts a chapter and he says,

111
00:05:43,000 --> 00:05:47,000
 "I want to talk to you now about something that we all struggle with."

112
00:05:47,000 --> 00:05:50,000
 It's like this beautiful pastoral moment.

113
00:05:50,000 --> 00:05:53,000
 He's kind of like slapped them around a bit, chapters one and two.

114
00:05:53,000 --> 00:05:58,000
 But in the third chapter, he's like, "I want to just express my heart for you guys."

115
00:05:58,000 --> 00:06:02,000
 He says, "I struggle with this. You struggle. We all struggle with this thing."

116
00:06:02,000 --> 00:06:07,000
 And in the chapter, he speaks about the power of words.

117
00:06:07,000 --> 00:06:09,000
 He speaks about what comes out of our mouths.

118
00:06:09,000 --> 00:06:14,000
 He speaks about the way in which we use our tongue, our language, and our words.

119
00:06:14,000 --> 00:06:19,000
 And I think it's important to James because I think James sees the much bigger picture.

120
00:06:19,000 --> 00:06:25,000
 I think he sees the reality of what God has done in creating human beings to be able to communicate.

121
00:06:25,000 --> 00:06:29,000
 I don't know if you've thought about it this way, but our words and our language and our communication,

122
00:06:29,000 --> 00:06:35,000
 it's the secret ingredients that aligns ourselves to either be able to draw closer to one another

123
00:06:35,000 --> 00:06:38,000
 or actually to push each other apart.

124
00:06:38,000 --> 00:06:41,000
 I don't know if you've thought about it that way, but essentially your words,

125
00:06:41,000 --> 00:06:47,000
 your ability to communicate is the process by which you as a human being can do the one thing

126
00:06:47,000 --> 00:06:52,000
 that every human being desires for the most, and that is intimacy.

127
00:06:52,000 --> 00:06:58,000
 We are literally created for relationship, created for intimacy.

128
00:06:58,000 --> 00:07:03,000
 And it is our communication, the way in which we speak, that brings that into our lives.

129
00:07:03,000 --> 00:07:09,000
 So in those seasons where we speak well and we speak life and we offer words of encouragement and love

130
00:07:09,000 --> 00:07:14,000
 and we connect well with people, we draw close and we are more intimate with the people around us.

131
00:07:14,000 --> 00:07:20,000
 But likewise, in those moments of life where we argue, where we slander, we gossip,

132
00:07:20,000 --> 00:07:24,000
 we find like stuff's not going down well and we communicate in ways that are rough or harsh,

133
00:07:24,000 --> 00:07:30,000
 we find ourselves at enmity with the people around us, pushing away from the people around us.

134
00:07:30,000 --> 00:07:35,000
 The actual word communication has an etymology that just basically means the roots within it.

135
00:07:35,000 --> 00:07:39,000
 And communication, the etymology of that is community.

136
00:07:39,000 --> 00:07:42,000
 And the etymology of community is communion.

137
00:07:42,000 --> 00:07:45,000
 Communion, this idea of drawing close and being intimate,

138
00:07:45,000 --> 00:07:50,000
 we just shared in what we call within the church world the communion table,

139
00:07:50,000 --> 00:07:54,000
 the place through the bread and the cup where we join in deeper relationship and intimacy

140
00:07:54,000 --> 00:07:57,000
 with the forgiveness of Christ and the power of His resurrection.

141
00:07:57,000 --> 00:08:02,000
 So communion forms out of community which is created by our communication.

142
00:08:02,000 --> 00:08:09,000
 So if we want greater communion with God and with one another, our communication is important.

143
00:08:09,000 --> 00:08:11,000
 When that goes wrong, community breaks.

144
00:08:11,000 --> 00:08:15,000
 And when community breaks, it is a struggle to find communion.

145
00:08:15,000 --> 00:08:22,000
 So when you think about the reality that God has literally created you for communion, for intimacy,

146
00:08:22,000 --> 00:08:25,000
 then your communication is central.

147
00:08:25,000 --> 00:08:29,000
 In other words, words really matter.

148
00:08:29,000 --> 00:08:31,000
 Like they really matter.

149
00:08:31,000 --> 00:08:35,000
 Not just because God wants you to be a nice person.

150
00:08:35,000 --> 00:08:39,000
 In fact, when you look at this chapter that we're going to unpack together today,

151
00:08:39,000 --> 00:08:44,000
 the temptation is to think really what James is just saying is, you know, change your behavior a little bit.

152
00:08:44,000 --> 00:08:46,000
 Like just try to say some nicer things.

153
00:08:46,000 --> 00:08:49,000
 But that's not at all what James is interested in.

154
00:08:49,000 --> 00:08:53,000
 He's not interested in some sort of behavior modification.

155
00:08:53,000 --> 00:08:58,000
 What James is interested in is helping all of us to understand the breadth and the beauty

156
00:08:58,000 --> 00:09:04,000
 of what God has done in this world and how that impacts us and our words that we speak

157
00:09:04,000 --> 00:09:12,000
 either align ourselves to the beauty and the wonder of God's kingdom or they dramatically take us away.

158
00:09:12,000 --> 00:09:18,000
 And you can sense this pastoral heart of James leaning out to his church, quietening his voice

159
00:09:18,000 --> 00:09:30,000
 and saying, "We're in this together, but I wonder whether we could together come truly, fully alive."

160
00:09:30,000 --> 00:09:36,000
 So what I want to do with you here this morning is take you on a bit of that journey through what James is teaching.

161
00:09:36,000 --> 00:09:43,000
 My prayer is that each one of us by the end would feel like there is a way for us to become more alive,

162
00:09:43,000 --> 00:09:46,000
 more the way that he has created us to be.

163
00:09:46,000 --> 00:09:50,000
 And to recognize that it's not about trying to say some nicer things,

164
00:09:50,000 --> 00:09:55,000
 but it's about understanding that the way in which we've been created to be

165
00:09:55,000 --> 00:10:01,000
 means that the words out of my mouth can bring life.

166
00:10:01,000 --> 00:10:07,000
 So let me show you this from James chapter 3. We're going to start in verse 2.

167
00:10:07,000 --> 00:10:10,000
 He actually speaks about words in three of his chapters because that's how important it is to him.

168
00:10:10,000 --> 00:10:16,000
 But let me just start chapter 3, verse 2. This is this. He says, "We all stumble in many ways."

169
00:10:16,000 --> 00:10:19,000
 Isn't that a beautiful pastoral way to start? Like he's not starting like,

170
00:10:19,000 --> 00:10:22,000
 "I've got three things I want to beat you around the head on today."

171
00:10:22,000 --> 00:10:27,000
 He starts by saying, "I'm in this boat with you. We're in this boat together.

172
00:10:27,000 --> 00:10:31,000
 We all stumble in so many ways."

173
00:10:31,000 --> 00:10:35,000
 He says, "If any person is never at fault in what they say,

174
00:10:35,000 --> 00:10:39,000
 they are a perfect person able to keep their whole body in check."

175
00:10:39,000 --> 00:10:44,000
 He's like, "Man, if you could get yourself, if you could be perfect in this, this is an amazing thing.

176
00:10:44,000 --> 00:10:47,000
 But here's the thing we all stumble with."

177
00:10:47,000 --> 00:10:53,000
 See, when we put bits into the mouths of horses to make them obey us, we can turn the whole animal.

178
00:10:53,000 --> 00:10:58,000
 Or take ships as an example. Although they are so large and driven by strong winds,

179
00:10:58,000 --> 00:11:03,000
 they are steered by a very small rudder whichever way the pilot wants it to go.

180
00:11:03,000 --> 00:11:08,000
 Likewise, the tongue. It is a small part of the body, but it makes great boasts.

181
00:11:08,000 --> 00:11:13,000
 Consider what a great forest is set on fire by such a small spark.

182
00:11:13,000 --> 00:11:18,000
 The tongue also is a fire, a weld of evil among the parts of the body.

183
00:11:18,000 --> 00:11:22,000
 It disrupts the whole person, sets the whole course of their life on fire,

184
00:11:22,000 --> 00:11:27,000
 and is itself set on fire by hell.

185
00:11:27,000 --> 00:11:33,000
 All kinds of animals, birds, reptiles, creatures of the sea are being tamed and have been tamed by people,

186
00:11:33,000 --> 00:11:39,000
 but no person can tame the tongue. It is a restless evil full of deadly poison.

187
00:11:39,000 --> 00:11:41,000
 And he says this, this is what we do.

188
00:11:41,000 --> 00:11:47,000
 "With the tongue we praise our Lord and Father, and with it we curse people who have been made in God's likeness.

189
00:11:47,000 --> 00:11:52,000
 Out of the same mouth come praise and cursing. My brothers and sisters, this should not be.

190
00:11:52,000 --> 00:11:55,000
 Can both fresh water and salt water flow from the same spring?

191
00:11:55,000 --> 00:12:00,000
 My brothers and sisters, can a fig tree bear olives? Can a grapevine bear figs?

192
00:12:00,000 --> 00:12:05,000
 Neither can a salt spring produce fresh water."

193
00:12:05,000 --> 00:12:10,000
 It's really beautiful here what James is trying to lean into his church.

194
00:12:10,000 --> 00:12:14,000
 He's like, "Don't you understand that there's this reality that we all stumble with,

195
00:12:14,000 --> 00:12:18,000
 and we all struggle with these words?" And he gives us three pictures to help us to see this.

196
00:12:18,000 --> 00:12:21,000
 He talks about the bit that's placed in a horse's mouth.

197
00:12:21,000 --> 00:12:24,000
 He talks about a rudder that's on a ship and how it steers.

198
00:12:24,000 --> 00:12:28,000
 But the one I want to dig into a little bit is the third image he gives us,

199
00:12:28,000 --> 00:12:33,000
 and it's of a spark that brings a fire to a whole forest.

200
00:12:33,000 --> 00:12:37,000
 And he talks about how this tongue is like a fire that is set on fire.

201
00:12:37,000 --> 00:12:39,000
 And then he goes all the way to the end of that passage, and he says,

202
00:12:39,000 --> 00:12:42,000
 "It's like it's burning, like the burning of hell."

203
00:12:42,000 --> 00:12:46,000
 And he uses this word that we translate into the English as hell.

204
00:12:46,000 --> 00:12:51,000
 And when we, in our time, read that word, we immediately think of the opposite of heaven.

205
00:12:51,000 --> 00:12:56,000
 We think that James is literally saying that the tongue can bring us into a place of hell,

206
00:12:56,000 --> 00:13:00,000
 as in this like eternal damnation away from heaven.

207
00:13:00,000 --> 00:13:05,000
 But actually, James is not using the word hell here. That's the word we translate.

208
00:13:05,000 --> 00:13:10,000
 He's actually naming a place that the Greek word here is the word Gehenna.

209
00:13:10,000 --> 00:13:17,000
 And Gehenna became the theme of which the New Testament begins to speak of the idea of hell.

210
00:13:17,000 --> 00:13:20,000
 But in this moment, James is speaking about a place.

211
00:13:20,000 --> 00:13:26,000
 He's naming a place that the people he's writing to would know about quite well.

212
00:13:26,000 --> 00:13:30,000
 Gehenna was about 50 miles south-southwest of Jerusalem.

213
00:13:30,000 --> 00:13:35,000
 And throughout the whole history of Israel in their land, it was a significant place.

214
00:13:35,000 --> 00:13:39,000
 In the Old Testament times, there were tribes that lived in the area of Gehenna.

215
00:13:39,000 --> 00:13:42,000
 Gehenna, interestingly, was a forest.

216
00:13:42,000 --> 00:13:47,000
 So notice in this part, he says, "A small spark that sets fire to a whole forest."

217
00:13:47,000 --> 00:13:50,000
 Gehenna was a forest area.

218
00:13:50,000 --> 00:13:56,000
 Now, what happened in the Old Testament times is that the tribes that lived there worshipped a god called Malak.

219
00:13:56,000 --> 00:14:02,000
 And Malak, the way they worshipped him, and this is horrible, trigger warning, but the reality,

220
00:14:02,000 --> 00:14:05,000
 they worshipped him through the sacrifice of children.

221
00:14:05,000 --> 00:14:10,000
 And the way they would do that is they would build a fire, a bonfire,

222
00:14:10,000 --> 00:14:16,000
 and then the child that was to be sacrificed was placed on the bonfire and was literally burned to death.

223
00:14:16,000 --> 00:14:20,000
 This was the worship to this Malak that was happening in that place.

